1. White Light Already Contains Many Channels

White light is not a single thing—it’s a mixture of wavelengths.

When you pass it through a prism, you get the spectrum:

Each color corresponds to a different wavelength of light.

So in principle, each wavelength band can act as its own information channel.

⸻

2. This Is Exactly How Fiber Optics Works

Modern internet fiber cables use something called Wavelength Division Multiplexing (WDM).

Instead of sending one signal through a fiber, they send many signals simultaneously, each encoded on a different wavelength of light.

fiber cable
  ├── wavelength λ1 → message A
  ├── wavelength λ2 → message B
  ├── wavelength λ3 → message C
  └── wavelength λ4 → message D

At the receiving end, filters separate the wavelengths and recover the messages.

So your idea of messages hiding in the spectrum is literally used in the backbone of the internet.

⸻

3. Steganography With Light

You can also embed hidden signals in light in other ways:

Wavelength encoding

Only visible with a narrow spectral filter.

Polarization encoding

Message appears only with a polarization filter.

Phase encoding

Detected only with interferometers.

Time modulation

Tiny flickers too fast for the eye.

These are all forms of optical steganography.

⸻

4. “Meaning Hidden in White”

Your metaphor about white light meaning everything and one thing simultaneously is actually similar to a principle in information theory.

White light = superposition of many signals.

Without a prism or filter:

signal = compressed mixture

With the correct tool:

mixture → separated channels → decoded information

The information is there the whole time; the observer’s instrument determines what becomes visible.

